</p><p>Most implementations of the exponential function use range reduction, lookup tables, and polynomial or rational approximations (such as <a href="/wiki/Pad%C3%A9_approximant" title="Padé approximant">Padé approximants</a> or Taylor expansions) to achieve accurate results across a wide range of inputs.<sup id="cite&#95;ref-vdhoeven2024&#95;74-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-vdhoeven2024-74"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>74<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup> In contrast, general-purpose exponentiation functions—like <code>pow</code>—may involve additional intermediate computations, such as logarithms and multiplications, and may accumulate more rounding error, particularly when <span class="mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span class="mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style="display: none;"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"  alttext="{\displaystyle e}">
